Labeling

Source: vignettes/labels.Rmd
labels.Rmd

The codebook function

Labels used in plots and tables are stored in the comment attribute of the variable. You can inspect all labels using the codebook()-function:

codebook(ds)
#> # A tibble: 97 × 6
#>    item_name     item_group item_class item_label         value_name value_label
#>    <chr>         <chr>      <chr>      <chr>              <chr>      <chr>      
#>  1 case          case       numeric    case               NA         NA         
#>  2 sd_age        sd         numeric    Age                NA         NA         
#>  3 cg_activities cg         character  Activities with C… NA         NA         
#>  4 cg_act_write  cg         character  cg_act_write       NA         NA         
#>  5 cg_act_test   cg         character  cg_act_test        NA         NA         
#>  6 cg_act_search cg         character  cg_act_search      NA         NA         
#>  7 adopter       adopter    factor     Innovator type     I try new… I try new …
#>  8 adopter       adopter    factor     Innovator type     I try new… I try new …
#>  9 adopter       adopter    factor     Innovator type     I wait un… I wait unt…
#> 10 adopter       adopter    factor     Innovator type     I only us… I only use…
#> # ℹ 87 more rows

To conveniently manage all labels of a dataset, you can save the result of codebook() to an Excel file, change the labels manually in a copy of the Excel file, and finally call labs_apply() with your revised codebook.


library(readxl)
library(writexl)

# Save codebook to a file
codes <- codebook(ds)
write_xlsx(codes,"codebook.xlsx")

# Load and apply a codebook from a file
codes <- read_xlsx("codebook_revised.xlsx")
ds <- labs_apply(codebook)

Change labels of selected items

You can set specific column labels by providing a named list to the items-parameter of labs_apply():

ds %>%
  labs_apply(
    items = list(
      "cg_adoption_advantage_01" = "Allgemeine Vorteile",
      "cg_adoption_advantage_02" = "Finanzielle Vorteile",
      "cg_adoption_advantage_03" = "Vorteile bei der Arbeit",
      "cg_adoption_advantage_04" = "Macht mehr Spaß"
    )
  ) %>% 
  tab_metrics(starts_with("cg_adoption_advantage_"))
Item min q1 median q3 max mean sd n
Allgemeine Vorteile 1 3 4 4 5 3.5 1.0 99
Finanzielle Vorteile 1 2 3 4 5 2.7 1.2 99
Vorteile bei der Arbeit 1 3 4 4 5 3.6 1.1 99
Macht mehr Spaß 1 3 4 4 5 3.5 1.0 99

n=99. 2 missing case(s) omitted.

Alternatively, you can use a dataframe in the codebook format. In this case, provide a tibble with item names in the first column and item labels in the second column.

The tribble function is a convenient way to construct the label tibble.

newlabels <- tribble(
  ~item_name, ~item_label,
  "cg_adoption_advantage_01", "Allgemeine Vorteile",
  "cg_adoption_advantage_02", "Finanzielle Vorteile",
  "cg_adoption_advantage_03", "Vorteile bei der Arbeit",
  "cg_adoption_advantage_04", "Macht mehr Spaß"
)

ds %>%
  labs_apply(newlabels) %>%
  tab_metrics(starts_with("cg_adoption_advantage_"))
Item min q1 median q3 max mean sd n
Allgemeine Vorteile 1 3 4 4 5 3.5 1.0 99
Finanzielle Vorteile 1 2 3 4 5 2.7 1.2 99
Vorteile bei der Arbeit 1 3 4 4 5 3.6 1.1 99
Macht mehr Spaß 1 3 4 4 5 3.5 1.0 99

n=99. 2 missing case(s) omitted.

Change labels of values in selected columns

Data values usally come in two forms:

  • Uncoded: Character values and factor values as well as metric values such as the age of a person can be analyzed and reported without further labeling. The values in the dataset speak for themselves. Usually you don’t relabel the values, you change them directly in the dataset.
  • Coded: Sometimes data values are numerically coded, for example from 1=disagree to 5 =agree. The values need to be labeled for reporting and interpretation.

Labels for both, coded and uncoded values, can be adjusted by providing a named list to the values-parameter of labs_apply(). In addition, select the columns where value labels should be changed:

Coded values example 


ds %>%
  labs_apply(
    cols=starts_with("cg_adoption"),  
    values = list(
      "1" = "Stimme überhaupt nicht zu",
      "2" = "Stimme nicht zu",
      "3" = "Unentschieden",
      "4" = "Stimme zu",
      "5" =  "Stimme voll und ganz zu"
    ) 
  ) %>% 
  plot_metrics(starts_with("cg_adoption"))

Uncoded (factor) values example 

ds %>%
  labs_apply(
    cols=sd_gender,  
    values = list(
      "female" = "Weiblich",
      "male" = "Männlich",
      "diverse" = "Divers"
    ) 
  ) |> 
  plot_counts(sd_gender)

Hint: To see the raw unlabeled values, call plot, tab, or report functions with the labels-parameter set to FALSE, e.g. plot_counts(ds, starts_with("cg_adoption"), labels = FALSE).

Alternatively, construct a tibble in codebook format, with the columns value_name and value_label. Tell labs_apply() in which columns value labels should be changed and set the values-parameter to TRUE.


newlabels <-  tribble(
  ~value_name, ~value_label,
  1, "Stimme überhaupt nicht zu",
  2, "Stimme nicht zu",
  3, "Unentschieden",
  4, "Stimme zu",
  5, "Stimme voll und ganz zu"
)  

ds |> 
  labs_apply(newlabels, cols=starts_with("cg_adoption")) |> 
  plot_metrics(starts_with("cg_adoption"))

Clear labels

You can remove all labels with labs_clear() to get a plain dataset.

ds %>%
  labs_clear(everything()) %>%
  tab_counts(starts_with("cg_adoption_advantage_"))
cg_adoption_advantage_0 -9 1 2 3 4 5 total
1 2% (2) 6% (6) 8% (8) 34% (34) 37% (37) 14% (14) 100% (101)
2 0% (0) 22% (22) 21% (21) 30% (30) 22% (22) 6% (6) 100% (101)
3 0% (0) 6% (6) 10% (10) 21% (21) 47% (47) 17% (17) 100% (101)
4 0% (0) 6% (6) 4% (4) 36% (36) 40% (40) 15% (15) 100% (101)

With the labels parameter, you achieve a similar result.

ds %>%
  tab_counts(starts_with("cg_adoption_advantage_"), labels= FALSE)
